00:01:44,929 --> 00:01:48,692
on the EVE sort of player base.

38
00:01:49,852 --> 00:01:51,253
The key thing here that I'll come back to

39
00:01:51,293 --> 00:01:52,234
is the 420,000 unique users logged in per month.

40
00:01:57,181 --> 00:02:03,806
Before we really dive into what I or we at CCP believe are the benefits and challenges of supporting third-party devs,

41
00:02:03,867 --> 00:02:08,490
I want to make sure we're all on the same page as to what we define third-party devs to be anyways.

42
00:02:09,551 --> 00:02:14,275
So to us, a third-party developer is someone outside of CCP who creates external content for our game,

43
00:02:15,136 --> 00:02:17,958
generally in the form of a desktop, web, or mobile application.

44
00:02:18,979 --> 00:02:20,560
It could also be spreadsheets or whatever.

45
00:02:21,801 --> 00:02:24,083
These developers are not paid by CCP in any way.

46
00:02:26,112 --> 00:02:29,734
and they don't receive any extra information that anyone else can't get.

47
00:02:29,894 --> 00:02:32,816
All of the resources we provide our third-party developers,

48
00:02:33,597 --> 00:02:35,998
whether it be our APIs or downloadable resources,

49
00:02:36,159 --> 00:02:39,621
are available to anyone, whether they classify themselves as a third-party dev or not.

50
00:02:42,699 --> 00:02:45,641
But what do we offer these third party devs in terms of

51
00:02:45,701 --> 00:02:47,082
resources to do cool things?

52
00:02:47,922 --> 00:02:51,305
We offer them first our image export collection, which is we

53
00:02:51,345 --> 00:02:53,186
gather up all the static images for a game.

54
00:02:53,206 --> 00:02:57,348
This is things like icons, renders that are not going to

55
00:02:57,388 --> 00:03:00,711
change, that are static renders between releases, UI

56
00:03:00,731 --> 00:03:03,652
elements as well, all get packaged up and released.

57
00:03:04,482 --> 00:03:06,442
We also offer our static data export.

58
00:03:06,462 --> 00:03:09,624
So this is a collection of static information for our

59
00:03:09,664 --> 00:03:12,765
games, such as item attributes, item names, the

60
00:03:12,985 --> 00:03:15,966
way the market's laid out, the universe data, all of that

61
00:03:16,026 --> 00:03:19,387
stuff that will not change between releases, packaged up

62
00:03:19,467 --> 00:03:20,728
and released to our third party devs.

63
00:03:22,288 --> 00:03:25,250
We give them access to our OAuth2 login, so they can add

64
00:03:25,290 --> 00:03:27,671
a Login with Eve button to their application,

65
00:03:27,711 --> 00:03:28,411
web page, whatever.

66
00:03:29,484 --> 00:03:31,125
We also give them access to our image server.

67
00:03:31,305 --> 00:03:32,925
This is something we use ourselves as well.

68
00:03:32,985 --> 00:03:36,067
And this is generally basically a CDN.

69
00:03:36,107 --> 00:03:38,788
It hosts a lot of the same images that are in the image

70
00:03:38,848 --> 00:03:41,969
export, but also dynamically generated images.

71
00:03:42,029 --> 00:03:44,990
So character portraits, that kind of stuff, corporation

72
00:03:45,030 --> 00:03:45,870
logos, whatever.

73
00:03:47,544 --> 00:03:49,786
We then give them access to two web APIs.

74
00:03:49,947 --> 00:03:51,148
The first is our XML API.

75
00:03:51,208 --> 00:03:52,250
It's our older API.

76
00:03:52,270 --> 00:03:54,373
It's been out, I think, since about 2004, 2005.

77
00:03:54,673 --> 00:03:57,156
And our Crest API.

78
00:03:57,316 --> 00:03:59,379
Crest stands for Carbon RESTful API.

79
00:04:00,401 --> 00:04:02,123
Both these are HTTP APIs.

80
00:04:03,244 --> 00:04:05,307
The Crest one is a JSON RESTful API.

81
00:04:06,588 --> 00:04:08,330
The XML API, as I said, it's our older one.

82
00:04:08,450 --> 00:04:12,052
It gets about 1,100 requests a second these days.

83
00:04:12,833 --> 00:04:16,215
And Crest is approaching 500 or 600 requests a second, just

84
00:04:16,255 --> 00:04:17,876
to give you an idea of where our APIs sit.

85
00:04:18,737 --> 00:04:20,518
The key difference between these two, aside from their

86
00:04:20,658 --> 00:04:23,921
age, the XML API sits outside of our game cluster.

87
00:04:24,221 --> 00:04:26,502
It has no access to the logic of the game or

88
00:04:26,542 --> 00:04:27,483
the runtime state.

89
00:04:27,563 --> 00:04:29,965
It only knows what's persisted to disk in the DB.

90
00:04:30,645 --> 00:04:32,627
So it just has read access to the DB.

91
00:04:33,488 --> 00:04:35,909
Crest, it runs on the cluster.

92
00:04:35,949 --> 00:04:37,010
It's part of the game.

93
00:04:37,090 --> 00:04:40,613
It was built for our second game, Dust 514, so that it can

94
00:04:40,833 --> 00:04:42,855
read and write to our cluster.

95
00:04:42,935 --> 00:04:44,756
And we're working on opening that up to our third party

96
00:04:44,776 --> 00:04:47,938
devs now, so they can both read and write to our game.

97
00:04:50,521 --> 00:04:58,269
And then briefly, what we feel internally are our guidelines to help us in developing resources for our third party devs.

98
00:04:58,810 --> 00:05:01,252
First and foremost, our client is off limits.

99
00:05:01,553 --> 00:05:06,598
There's no UI mods, no mods of any kind, anything like that will get you banned permanently from our game.

100
00:05:07,339 --> 00:05:11,040
We do this because we firmly believe, as our game is a competitive game,

101
00:05:11,640 --> 00:05:15,102
when you get into a fight, it is up to your skill using our client.

102
00:05:15,122 --> 00:05:18,063
We don't want you to have to go and download something just to be competitive,

103
00:05:18,503 --> 00:05:19,764
which is kind of our second point.

104
00:05:20,224 --> 00:05:23,626
You should not have to download any application to be competitive at EVE.

105
00:05:23,966 --> 00:05:27,347
You can have an application that helps you find a fight, that kind of thing,

106
00:05:27,387 --> 00:05:29,828
but once you're in a fight, it's your skill at our game

107
00:05:29,848 --> 00:05:31,709
that's going to sort of determine who wins.

108
00:05:33,150 --> 00:05:35,151
So those two kind of play off each other, and the third one

109
00:05:35,191 --> 00:05:38,072
just builds on that, which is no information should be

110
00:05:38,092 --> 00:05:40,993
available to our third party devs that you cannot get in

111
00:05:41,013 --> 00:05:41,593
the client.

112
00:05:42,333 --> 00:05:44,134
This is, again, just to help support the

113
00:05:44,374 --> 00:05:45,274
first two points there.

114
00:05:48,275 --> 00:05:50,356
So the first benefit I really want to talk to you guys about

115
00:05:50,736 --> 00:05:53,817
is how third party developers can help you deal with the

116
00:05:53,877 --> 00:05:55,018
scope of features in your game.

117
00:05:56,202 --> 00:05:58,722
For us, we generally start when we're designing a new feature,

118
00:05:58,883 --> 00:06:00,003
very blue sky, right?

119
00:06:00,023 --> 00:06:02,604
We design the feature to cover as many use cases as possible.

120
00:06:02,624 --> 00:06:04,785
We're brainstorming the biggest, greatest feature ever.

121
00:06:05,625 --> 00:06:07,966
We scope this down and prioritize it and start work

122
00:06:08,066 --> 00:06:08,586
on it, right?

123
00:06:09,646 --> 00:06:11,907
During development, sometimes things get cut.

124
00:06:11,927 --> 00:06:13,608
This is either because we've run out of time,

125
00:06:14,048 --> 00:06:15,328
the thing was too difficult to do,

126
00:06:16,448 --> 00:06:18,849
whatever problem came up, or we just

127
00:06:18,889 --> 00:06:21,810
felt this thing we were going to do, part of this feature,

128
00:06:22,110 --> 00:06:24,391
wasn't going to fit our game, wasn't going to fit our client.

129
00:06:24,811 --> 00:06:25,351
So we cut it.

130
00:06:26,621 --> 00:06:28,562
For the most part, this is generally where things then

131
00:06:28,602 --> 00:06:29,143
get shipped.

132
00:06:29,723 --> 00:06:32,705
For us, what we try and do, however, is during that

133
00:06:32,766 --> 00:06:36,548
development, expose it in one of our APIs, whether it's XML,

134
00:06:36,668 --> 00:06:39,531
API, or Crest, or add it to the static data export.

135
00:06:41,072 --> 00:06:42,773
And we have a very easy framework for

136
00:06:42,833 --> 00:06:43,674
doing that these days.

137
00:06:43,734 --> 00:06:47,156
So if a team would like to add something to the API, it

138
00:06:47,196 --> 00:06:49,718
doesn't take much effort, doesn't take much more than

139
00:06:49,738 --> 00:06:52,080
they've already put in to develop the feature to get it

140
00:06:52,220 --> 00:06:54,221
added and exposed to our third-party developers.

141
00:06:56,243 --> 00:06:57,905
But I mean, OK, so that's what we do.

142
00:06:57,925 --> 00:06:59,266
But why expose the data?

143
00:06:59,406 --> 00:07:01,409
And how does it help us deal with the scope of a feature?

144
00:07:02,190 --> 00:07:04,552
The best way to go about this, I think, is with an example.

145
00:07:05,834 --> 00:07:07,696
This is a screenshot of the wallet in our game.

146
00:07:07,796 --> 00:07:10,599
Shows you all of the money coming into your character

147
00:07:10,799 --> 00:07:12,261
and the money that your character is spending.

148
00:07:14,114 --> 00:07:15,655
It works pretty well for small groups, right?

149
00:07:15,755 --> 00:07:18,218
You can paginate forward and backwards.

150
00:07:18,318 --> 00:07:20,780
You can put in a specific date and load the transactions from

151
00:07:20,800 --> 00:07:21,201
that date.

152
00:07:21,801 --> 00:07:24,044
You can filter by transaction type if you only want

153
00:07:24,084 --> 00:07:26,947
transactions for market stuff or player trades.

154
00:07:27,904 --> 00:07:33,548
And then you get a very quick rundown, sort of summary of the money coming in and out and your total balance.

155
00:07:34,169 --> 00:07:37,952
So again, this works wonderful for small groups or an individual, right?

156
00:07:38,012 --> 00:07:40,294
Small groups, 10, 20, even maybe 100.

157
00:07:41,095 --> 00:07:45,879
But we tend to have groups in our game, as we're a single sharded game, that go up to 3,000, 10,000.

158
00:07:46,259 --> 00:07:50,342
There's a coalition of 40,000 players in our game.

159
00:07:50,843 --> 00:07:53,105
This wallet tends to fall apart at that scale.

160
00:07:54,600 --> 00:07:57,543
So very early on, before we even really realized how

161
00:07:57,583 --> 00:07:59,444
important third-party developers were to us, one of

162
00:07:59,464 --> 00:08:02,387
the things we added to the XML API was the wallet.

163
00:08:02,527 --> 00:08:04,649
And this is exactly the same information you see in this

164
00:08:04,690 --> 00:08:05,430
screenshot here.

165
00:08:06,291 --> 00:08:11,756
It's who the transaction was between, the transaction type,

166
00:08:11,776 --> 00:08:14,739
the time, how much it was for, all that kind of stuff.

167
00:08:15,140 --> 00:08:18,343
Just grabbed from our database, formatted for XML,

168
00:08:18,383 --> 00:08:18,923
and dumped out.

169
00:08:21,330 --> 00:08:25,414
What I'm about to show you is a public financial release from

170
00:08:25,454 --> 00:08:26,355
one of our organizations.

171
00:08:26,395 --> 00:08:28,396
They're a 3,000-member organization known as

172
00:08:28,437 --> 00:08:29,177
Pandemic Legion.

173
00:08:29,457 --> 00:08:31,519
And it covers 18 months of their alliance.

174
00:08:33,041 --> 00:08:35,783
So very simply, it shows the income and expenditure of

175
00:08:35,824 --> 00:08:37,725
their alliance over time.

176
00:08:38,866 --> 00:08:41,008
Same sort of thing, just broken down by subgroup or

177
00:08:41,129 --> 00:08:43,731
corporation in the alliance, how much they were spending.

178
00:08:45,475 --> 00:08:48,237
by corporation over time, pretty straightforward, right?

179
00:08:48,738 --> 00:08:55,143
Then they start breaking it down by category, or I'm not sure how they define these, but they're a type of category, I guess.

180
00:08:58,226 --> 00:09:02,549
This is the fuel usage over 18 months by the corporations in this alliance,

181
00:09:02,609 --> 00:09:06,373
and sort of who was spending the most fuel, and then broken down by fuel type.

182
00:09:07,977 --> 00:09:09,277
So that was all really cool, right?

183
00:09:09,517 --> 00:09:10,917
Really nice and pretty graphs.

184
00:09:10,977 --> 00:09:14,358
It makes for great content, nice news articles written

185
00:09:14,378 --> 00:09:17,119
about this, financial report, and that kind of stuff.

186
00:09:17,719 --> 00:09:22,220
But if it's so cool, why do we not offer that in the client?

187
00:09:23,201 --> 00:09:26,381
Well, to be honest, we could add all those features in the

188
00:09:26,441 --> 00:09:29,202
client, and they'd be used by no one.

189
00:09:29,882 --> 00:09:32,703
And the reason I say that is Pandemic Legion or any other

190
00:09:32,763 --> 00:09:33,983
organization of that scale.

191
00:09:35,310 --> 00:09:38,095
they really only have one guy dealing with their finances, right?

192
00:09:38,295 --> 00:09:40,940
And that one guy probably wants Excel.

193
00:09:43,004 --> 00:09:45,429
But also, and this is sort of more important,

194
00:09:48,090 --> 00:09:52,654
Not sure if you can read it, but there's a section there called Espionage or Special Projects.

195
00:09:52,914 --> 00:09:54,755
Then there's another one called FanFest.

196
00:09:55,215 --> 00:09:58,358
FanFest is our player gathering in Iceland that happens once a year.

197
00:09:58,678 --> 00:10:01,720
I have no idea how they're spending in-game money on that. I don't know.

198
00:10:03,061 --> 00:10:07,964
Special Projects or Espionage. Again, I have absolutely no idea what they define as that.

199
00:10:08,765 --> 00:10:12,588
Our game is a sandbox, we give them tools, what they do with those tools is up to them.

200
00:10:12,648 --> 00:10:14,469
So a lot of this is emergent gameplay.

201
00:10:15,030 --> 00:10:19,593
They're infiltrating a corporation and I guess probably spending some money to pay for that

202
00:10:19,814 --> 00:10:25,118
alt or whatever, but we have no way of tracking that in the game, right?

203
00:10:26,199 --> 00:10:30,382
So we could spend a lot of time developing this feature, trying to build a replica of

204
00:10:30,442 --> 00:10:32,183
Excel in our client.

205
00:10:33,036 --> 00:10:36,143
But then we're probably going to miss a lot of these special edge cases

206
00:10:36,183 --> 00:10:39,230
that our players want, because we don't know what they are.

207
00:10:39,250 --> 00:10:40,813
This is a sandbox.

208
00:10:40,853 --> 00:10:41,875
It's emergent gameplay.

209
00:10:44,816 --> 00:10:54,919
And just serve as a few other examples of areas that our third-party developers have created tools or resources to help in areas that we didn't even know existed or needed features.

210
00:10:55,619 --> 00:11:06,063
Character trading. We offer an authorized way of transferring a character between two accounts and players will bid ISK or our in-game currency to buy these other characters.

211
00:11:07,143 --> 00:11:12,505
And they can take the word of someone that says, well, I'm selling this character and he has these stats and this much money.

212
00:11:13,145 --> 00:11:15,446
But then you're relying on that character, or that person,

213
00:11:15,466 --> 00:11:17,167
to be telling you the truth about that character.

214
00:11:17,187 --> 00:11:20,629
Via our API, there's a person that's set up a,

215
00:11:20,789 --> 00:11:22,630
he's a trusted person, a trusted player,

216
00:11:23,070 --> 00:11:25,151
and he's set up a website that'll pull all this information

217
00:11:25,191 --> 00:11:27,612
from the API and tell you it's API verified

218
00:11:27,632 --> 00:11:29,793
and what this guy is telling you is true, right?

219
00:11:30,494 --> 00:11:31,955
So that helps with character trading,

220
00:11:31,995 --> 00:11:33,175
which is, I don't think,

221
00:11:33,215 --> 00:11:35,076
anything we originally thought would exist.

222
00:11:36,242 --> 00:11:37,583
Planetary income monitoring.

223
00:11:37,623 --> 00:11:38,924
You can own planets in our game.

224
00:11:38,944 --> 00:11:40,985
And when players use those planets as the owner,

225
00:11:41,026 --> 00:11:42,026
you get a cut of that.

226
00:11:42,206 --> 00:11:43,367
You get to tax it, right?

227
00:11:44,628 --> 00:11:45,649
And that will show up in your wallet.

228
00:11:45,669 --> 00:11:47,230
And again, it works great for small groups.

229
00:11:47,270 --> 00:11:50,432
If you own a planet, half a dozen or a dozen planets,

230
00:11:50,472 --> 00:11:51,252
it works fine.

231
00:11:51,633 --> 00:11:54,214
But when you own 500 planets, and you

232
00:11:54,234 --> 00:11:57,296
want to know which planets are generating the most income

233
00:11:57,357 --> 00:12:00,318
for you, and you own 500 planets, and 30 of them

234
00:12:00,399 --> 00:12:02,840
come under attack, which one do you defend?

235
00:12:02,880 --> 00:12:04,521
You need to be able to track all this information.

236
00:12:04,541 --> 00:12:05,462
You want to track things like.

237
00:12:05,982 --> 00:12:09,026
which corporations are paying you the most, maybe you make them a deal,

238
00:12:09,066 --> 00:12:12,050
or trying to attract more people into using your planets, right?

239
00:12:12,671 --> 00:12:17,096
All this sort of stuff, which applies to like three or four organizations in our game.

240
00:12:17,617 --> 00:12:20,720
So we could again spend a bunch of time developing these features in our client,

241
00:12:21,261 --> 00:12:24,465
